answers.body_markdown:
You should not do this:

&gt;     delete *e;
&gt;     (*e)-&gt;head-&gt;edge_ins.erase(e);
&gt;     return (*e)-&gt;root-&gt;edge_outs.erase(e);

Once a pointer has been deleted you should not try to dereference it, otherwise you will get a segmentation fault or some other undefined behaviour. Consider changing the order of the statements and the return type of delete_edge like so:

    void SDG::delete_edge(std::set&lt;Edge*&gt;::iterator e)
    {
        (*e)-&gt;head-&gt;edge_ins.erase(e);
        (*e)-&gt;root-&gt;edge_outs.erase(e);
        delete *e;
    }

This will erase the pointer from the sets before deleting the pointer itself.

Something else you should consider is using a smart pointer (`std::shared_ptr&lt;Edge&gt;`) instead of raw pointers. Then you don&#39;t have to do the memory management yourself, i.e. calling delete, because the memory will be managed by the smart pointer. A shared pointer will delete the memory on the heap when the last shared pointer to that resource is destroyed. Then you can change the function like so:

    void SDG::delete_edge(std::set&lt;std::shared_ptr&lt;Edge&gt;&gt;::iterator e)
    {
        (*e)-&gt;head-&gt;edge_ins.erase(e);
        (*e)-&gt;root-&gt;edge_outs.erase(e);
    }

and the sets should be of type `std::set&lt;std::shared_ptr&lt;Edge&gt;&gt;`. Here&#39;s an [example][1] of how to create a shared pointer. In your case you can create it like this in the function edge():

    std::shared_ptr&lt;Edge&gt; edge = std::make_shared&lt;Edge&gt;(type, *out, *in);

Using shared pointers will avoid the problem of double deletes, which seems to be happening in your code. Otherwise you have to do the memory management yourself and avoid deleting a pointer twice.


  [1]: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/memory/shared_ptr/make_shared

